    <GeneralDescription>
      <![CDATA[<p style='line-height:1.5'><b><span style='color:#0070C0'>Income
concepts: </span></b></p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><u>Market/Original incomes</u>
are the sum of income from employment and self-employment plus income from
other sources. Other sources include income from investment, property, private
pensions, private transfers, children younger than 16, minus private transfers
paid to other households. See income list ils_origy in the country models.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><u>Disposable incomes</u> are
the sum of market incomes and benefits (incl. pensions) minus taxes and social
insurance contributions. See income list ils_dispy in the country models. 
<u>Equivalised disposable income</u> is the total
disposable household income divided by the modified OECD scale to take
differences in household composition into account. The <u>modified OECD</u>
scale attributes a weight of 1 to the head of the household, a weight of 0.5 to
every person above the age of 14 and a weight of 0.3 to every child aged 0-14.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><u>Decile groups</u> are
calculated by ranking individuals according to their <u>equivalised</u>
disposable household income and dividing them into ten similar-sized groups.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'>All monetary amounts – except
for the fiscal overview – are presented in average monthly amounts and in the
currency defined in the Euromod output file.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><b><span style='color:#0070C0'>Poverty
indicators:</span></b></p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'>Households are defined as <u>being
at risk of poverty (poor)</u> if their equivalised disposable household income
is below the poverty line. <u>The poverty line</u> is defined as 60% of the
country specific median equivalised disposable household income. The <u>poverty
gap</u> is the difference between the poverty line and the median income of
people at-risk-of poverty divided by the poverty line. The median income of
people at-risk-of poverty is based on equivalised disposable income.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'>NOTE: negative equivalised
disposable household incomes are recoded to 0 for all poverty related results.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><b><span style='color:#0070C0'>Inequality
indicators:</span></b></p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><u>Gini</u> measures the
distribution of income within a country where 0 means perfect income equality
and 1 means perfect income inequality. </p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'>The <u>S80/20 ratio</u> - also
referred to as the income quintile share ratio – is the ratio of the total
income received by the 20% of the population with the highest income to that
received by the bottom 20%. </p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'>NOTE: negative incomes are
recoded to 0 for results on Gini and S80/20 indicators.</p>

<p style='line-height:1.5'><b><span style='color:#0070C0'>Definition
of age-groups:</span></b></p>

<p style='margin-bottom:0cm;margin-bottom:.0001pt;line-height:1.5'>Sub-population groups are defined as follows:</p>

<p style='margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:0cm;
margin-left:36.0pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:1.5'><span style='font-family:Symbol'>·    </span><u>Children</u> are persons
aged 18 or younger</p>

<p style='margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:0cm;
margin-left:36.0pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:1.5'><span style='font-family:Symbol'>·    </span><u>Working Age are</u>
persons older than 18 up to the age of 64</p>

<p style='margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:0cm;
margin-left:36.0pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:1.5'><span style='font-family:Symbol'>·    </span>Someone is <u>economically
active</u> if he/she has income from employment or self-employment </p>

<p style='margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:0cm;
margin-left:36.0pt;margin-bottom:.0001pt;text-indent:-18.0pt;line-height:1.5'><span style='font-family:Symbol'>·    </span><u>Elderly</u> are persons
aged 65 or older</p>]]></GeneralDescription>
